  "prompt": "Why do flights from India to USA not travel via the north pole?",
  "response": "Flights from India to the USA typically do not travel directly over the North Pole for several reasons:\n\n1. Great Circle Route\n- The most direct route between India and the USA is not necessarily via the North Pole\n- The shortest path (great circle route) depends on the specific departure and arrival cities\n\n2. Wind Patterns\n- Jet streams and prevailing winds can significantly impact flight efficiency\n- Routes are planned to take advantage of favorable wind conditions\n\n3. Safety Considerations\n- Extreme cold and potential communication/navigation challenges near the North Pole\n- Limited emergency landing options in remote Arctic regions\n\n4. Geopolitical Restrictions\n- Some countries restrict overflights through their airspace\n- Political tensions or airspace regulations can impact route selection\n\n5. Aircraft Technical Limitations\n- Not all aircraft are equipped for extended polar operations\n- Special navigation and communication systems are required for polar routes\n\n6. Fuel Efficiency\n- The actual most efficient route might not be a straight line over the pole\n- Airlines optimize routes for fuel consumption and overall trip time\n\nWhile some transpacific or transatlantic flights do use polar routes, the specific route between India and the USA depends on multiple complex factors determined by airlines and aviation authorities.",
